Feng Tian

I work at Wuhan University, interested in monitoring vegetation dynamics with Earth observation data and understanding Earth system processes. I did my PhD at University of Copenhagen and earned the Faculty PhD prize in 2017. I also got the EU Marie-Curie postdoctoral fellowship hosted by Lund University to continue research on African semi-arid ecosystems, based on which I had two field trips to Senegal and Zambia. After joining Wuhan University, I extend my research to global mountains and current I am establishing a field site at Nyingchi (Linzhi) in southeastern Tibet Pleatau.

Education

University of Copenhagen | Denmark

PhD in Physical Geography | September 2013 - September 2016

China University of Mining & Technology | Xuzhou, China

Successive Master and PhD student in Remote Sensing | September 2010 - May 2013

Inner Mongolia Agriculture University | Hohhot, China

B.S. in Surveying and Mapping Engineering | August 2006 - July 2010

Employment

Wuhan University| Faculty | August 2020 - Present

Lund University| Researcher | January 2020 - July 2020

Lund University| Marie-Curie Postdoc Fellow | January 2018 - December 2019

University of Copenhagen| Postdoc | September 2016 - December 2017
